Therefore, to maximize the chance of receiving your most-preferred feasible match, you should rank companies exactly according to your true preferences.

This procedure is the Top Trading Cycles (TTC) style algorithm: in each round, each seeker points to their top remaining company and each company points to its top remaining seeker; any cycles are finalized. In round 1, Seeker_A, Seeker_C, Seeker_D, and I (Seeker_E) all point to Company_D, while Seeker_B points to Company_E. Companies point to: A->E, B->D, C->D, D->B, E->A. This creates a fixed 2-cycle: Seeker_B -> Company_E -> Seeker_A -> Company_D -> Seeker_B, which finalizes (B,E) and (A,D) immediately, removing Company_D (my top choice) before I can access it. In round 2, remaining seekers are C, D, E and remaining companies are A, B, C. Then C points to C, D points to B, and I can choose between C/B/A. Company_C’s top remaining seeker is me (E), so if I rank Company_C above Company_B, I form an immediate 2-cycle (E<->C) and secure Company_C. If I instead rank Company_B above Company_C, Company_B points to D and I would not be in a cycle, and I could end up at Company_A (worst). Therefore, to maximize my outcome, I should put Company_C at the top of my submitted list (even though D and E are my true top two, they are effectively unattainable here), followed by Company_B, then Company_A.
